32/* Available CPU feature flags */
33#define CPU_Any 0 /* Any old cpu will do */
34#define CPU_086 CPU_Any
35#define CPU_186 1 /* i186 or better required */
36#define CPU_286 2 /* i286 or better required */
37#define CPU_386 3 /* i386 or better required */
38#define CPU_486 4 /* i486 or better required */
39#define CPU_586 5 /* i585 or better required */
40#define CPU_686 6 /* i686 or better required */
41#define CPU_P3 7 /* Pentium3 or better required */
42#define CPU_P4 8 /* Pentium4 or better required */
43#define CPU_IA64 9 /* IA-64 or better required */
44#define CPU_K6 10 /* AMD K6 or better required */
45#define CPU_Athlon 11 /* AMD Athlon or better required */
46#define CPU_Hammer 12 /* AMD Sledgehammer or better required */
47#define CPU_FPU 13 /* FPU support required */
48#define CPU_MMX 14 /* MMX support required */
49#define CPU_SSE 15 /* Streaming SIMD extensions required */
50#define CPU_SSE2 16 /* Streaming SIMD extensions 2 required */
51#define CPU_SSE3 17 /* Streaming SIMD extensions 3 required */
52#define CPU_3DNow 18 /* 3DNow! support required */
53#define CPU_Cyrix 19 /* Cyrix-specific instruction */
54#define CPU_AMD 20 /* AMD-specific inst. (older than K6) */
55#define CPU_SMM 21 /* System Management Mode instruction */
56#define CPU_Prot 22 /* Protected mode only instruction */
57#define CPU_Undoc 23 /* Undocumented instruction */
58#define CPU_Obs 24 /* Obsolete instruction */
59#define CPU_Priv 25 /* Priveleged instruction */
60#define CPU_SVM 26 /* Secure Virtual Machine instruction */
61#define CPU_PadLock 27 /* VIA PadLock instruction */
62#define CPU_EM64T 28 /* Intel EM64T or better */
63#define CPU_SSSE3 29 /* Streaming SIMD extensions 3 required */
64#define CPU_SSE41 30 /* Streaming SIMD extensions 4.1 required */
65#define CPU_SSE42 31 /* Streaming SIMD extensions 4.2 required */
66#define CPU_SSE4a 32 /* AMD Streaming SIMD extensions 4a required */
67#define CPU_XSAVE 33 /* Intel XSAVE instructions */
68#define CPU_AVX 34 /* Intel Advanced Vector Extensions */
69#define CPU_FMA 35 /* Intel Fused-Multiply-Add Extensions */
70#define CPU_AES 36 /* AES instruction */
71#define CPU_CLMUL 37 /* PCLMULQDQ instruction */
72#define CPU_MOVBE 38 /* MOVBE instruction */
73#define CPU_XOP 39 /* AMD XOP extensions */
74#define CPU_FMA4 40 /* AMD Fused-Multiply-Add extensions */
75#define CPU_F16C 41 /* Intel float-16 instructions */
76#define CPU_FSGSBASE 42 /* Intel FSGSBASE instructions */
77#define CPU_RDRAND 43 /* Intel RDRAND instruction */
78#define CPU_XSAVEOPT 44 /* Intel XSAVEOPT instruction */
79#define CPU_EPTVPID 45 /* Intel INVEPT, INVVPID instructions */
80#define CPU_SMX 46 /* Intel SMX instruction (GETSEC) */
81#define CPU_AVX2 47 /* Intel AVX2 instructions */
82#define CPU_BMI1 48 /* Intel BMI1 instructions */
83#define CPU_BMI2 49 /* Intel BMI2 instructions */
84#define CPU_INVPCID 50 /* Intel INVPCID instruction */
85#define CPU_LZCNT 51 /* Intel LZCNT instruction */
86#define CPU_TBM 52 /* AMD TBM instruction */
87#define CPU_TSX 53 /* Intel TSX instructions */
88#define CPU_SHA 54 /* Intel SHA instructions */
89#define CPU_SMAP 55 /* Intel SMAP instructions */
90#define CPU_RDSEED 56 /* Intel RDSEED instruction */
91#define CPU_ADX 57 /* Intel ADCX and ADOX instructions */
92#define CPU_PRFCHW 58 /* Intel/AMD PREFETCHW instruction */

94enum x86_parser_type {
95 X86_PARSER_NASM = 0,
96 X86_PARSER_TASM = 1,
97 X86_PARSER_GAS = 2
98};
99
100#define PARSER(arch) (((arch)->parser == X86_PARSER_GAS && (arch)->gas_intel_mode) ? X86_PARSER_NASM : (arch)->parser)
101
102typedef struct yasm_arch_x86 {
103 yasm_arch_base arch; /* base structure */
104
105 /* What instructions/features are enabled? */
106 unsigned int active_cpu; /* active index into cpu_enables table */
107 unsigned int cpu_enables_size; /* size of cpu_enables table */
108 wordptr *cpu_enables;
109
110 unsigned int amd64_machine;
111 enum x86_parser_type parser;
112 unsigned int mode_bits;
113 unsigned int address_size;
114 unsigned int force_strict;
115 unsigned int default_rel;
116 unsigned int gas_intel_mode;
117
118 enum {
119 X86_NOP_BASIC = 0,
120 X86_NOP_INTEL = 1,
121 X86_NOP_AMD = 2
122 } nop;
123} yasm_arch_x86;
124
125/* 0-15 (low 4 bits) used for register number, stored in same data area.
126 * Note 8-15 are only valid for some registers, and only in 64-bit mode.
127 */
128typedef enum {
129 X86_REG8 = 0x1<<4,
130 X86_REG8X = 0x2<<4, /* 64-bit mode only, REX prefix version of REG8 */
131 X86_REG16 = 0x3<<4,
132 X86_REG32 = 0x4<<4,
133 X86_REG64 = 0x5<<4, /* 64-bit mode only */
134 X86_FPUREG = 0x6<<4,
135 X86_MMXREG = 0x7<<4,
136 X86_XMMREG = 0x8<<4,
137 X86_YMMREG = 0x9<<4,
138 X86_CRREG = 0xA<<4,
139 X86_DRREG = 0xB<<4,
140 X86_TRREG = 0xC<<4,
141 X86_RIP = 0xD<<4 /* 64-bit mode only, always RIP (regnum ignored) */
142} x86_expritem_reg_size;
143
144/* Low 8 bits are used for the prefix value, stored in same data area. */
145typedef enum {
146 X86_LOCKREP = 1<<8,
147 X86_ADDRSIZE = 2<<8,
148 X86_OPERSIZE = 3<<8,
149 X86_SEGREG = 4<<8,
150 X86_REX = 5<<8,
151 X86_ACQREL = 6<<8 /*TSX hint prefixes*/
152} x86_parse_insn_prefix;
153
154typedef enum {
155 X86_NEAR = 1,
156 X86_SHORT,
157 X86_FAR,
158 X86_TO
159} x86_parse_targetmod;
160
161typedef enum {
162 JMP_NONE,
163 JMP_SHORT,
164 JMP_NEAR,
165 JMP_SHORT_FORCED,
166 JMP_NEAR_FORCED
167} x86_jmp_opcode_sel;
168
169typedef enum {
170 X86_REX_W = 3,
171 X86_REX_R = 2,
172 X86_REX_X = 1,
173 X86_REX_B = 0
174} x86_rex_bit_pos;
175
176/* Sets REX (4th bit) and 3 LS bits from register size/number. Returns 1 if
177 * impossible to fit reg into REX, otherwise returns 0. Input parameter rexbit
178 * indicates bit of REX to use if REX is needed. Will not modify REX if not
179 * in 64-bit mode or if it wasn't needed to express reg.
180 */
181int yasm_x86__set_rex_from_reg(unsigned char *rex, unsigned char *low3,
182 uintptr_t reg, unsigned int bits,
183 x86_rex_bit_pos rexbit);
184
185/* Effective address type */
186typedef struct x86_effaddr {
187 yasm_effaddr ea; /* base structure */
188
189 /* VSIB uses the normal SIB byte, but this flag enables it. */
190 unsigned char vsib_mode; /* 0 if not, 1 if XMM, 2 if YMM */
191
192 /* How the spare (register) bits in Mod/RM are handled:
193 * Even if valid_modrm=0, the spare bits are still valid (don't overwrite!)
194 * They're set in bytecode_create_insn().
195 */
196 unsigned char modrm;
197 unsigned char valid_modrm; /* 1 if Mod/RM byte currently valid, 0 if not */
198 unsigned char need_modrm; /* 1 if Mod/RM byte needed, 0 if not */
199
200 unsigned char sib;
201 unsigned char valid_sib; /* 1 if SIB byte currently valid, 0 if not */
202 unsigned char need_sib; /* 1 if SIB byte needed, 0 if not,
203 0xff if unknown */
204} x86_effaddr;

226/* Bytecode types */
227typedef struct x86_common {
228 unsigned char addrsize; /* 0 or =mode_bits => no override */
229 unsigned char opersize; /* 0 or =mode_bits => no override */
230 unsigned char lockrep_pre; /* 0 indicates no prefix */
231 unsigned char acqrel_pre; /* 0 indicates no prefix. We need this because
232 xqcuire/xrelease might require F0 prefix */
233
234 unsigned char mode_bits;
235} x86_common;
236
237typedef struct x86_opcode {
238 unsigned char opcode[3]; /* opcode */
239 unsigned char len;
240} x86_opcode;
241
242typedef struct x86_insn {
243 x86_common common; /* common x86 information */
244 x86_opcode opcode;
245
246 /*@null@*/ x86_effaddr *x86_ea; /* effective address */
247
248 /*@null@*/ yasm_value *imm; /* immediate or relative value */
249
250 unsigned char def_opersize_64; /* default operand size in 64-bit mode */
251 unsigned char special_prefix; /* "special" prefix (0=none) */
252
253 unsigned char rex; /* REX AMD64 extension, 0 if none,
254 0xff if not allowed (high 8 bit reg used) */
255
256 /* Postponed (from parsing to later binding) action options. */
257 enum {
258 /* None */
259 X86_POSTOP_NONE = 0,
260
261 /* Instructions that take a sign-extended imm8 as well as imm values
262 * (eg, the arith instructions and a subset of the imul instructions)
263 * should set this and put the imm8 form as the "normal" opcode (in
264 * the first one or two bytes) and non-imm8 form in the second or
265 * third byte of the opcode.
266 */
267 X86_POSTOP_SIGNEXT_IMM8,
268
269 /* Override any attempt at address-size override to 16 bits, and never
270 * generate a prefix. This is used for the ENTER opcode.
271 */
272 X86_POSTOP_ADDRESS16
273 } postop;
274} x86_insn;
275
276typedef struct x86_jmp {
277 x86_common common; /* common x86 information */
278 x86_opcode shortop, nearop;
279
280 yasm_value target; /* jump target */
281
282 /* which opcode are we using? */
283 /* The *FORCED forms are specified in the source as such */
284 x86_jmp_opcode_sel op_sel;
285} x86_jmp;
286
287/* Direct (immediate) FAR jumps ONLY; indirect FAR jumps get turned into
288 * x86_insn bytecodes; relative jumps turn into x86_jmp bytecodes.
289 * This bytecode is not legal in 64-bit mode.
290 */
291typedef struct x86_jmpfar {
292 x86_common common; /* common x86 information */
293 x86_opcode opcode;
294
295 yasm_value segment; /* target segment */
296 yasm_value offset; /* target offset */
297} x86_jmpfar;
